TO NURSE RATCHET<br><br>
&gt;To Doc Del- I'm sorry, but I just don't agree with you that &quot;the general population at large&quot; mistreated Vietnam Vets during the war and beyond the war years. As I've said before, there were protestors who spat, called names, etc. And I'm sure there are still people who may see VVets as baby killers, rapists, whatever. But in the last 35 years I've never met any of 'em. I find it very hard to believe that those kind of people were not a small minority. Of<br>
course, I don't know how you define &quot;mistreatment.&quot; I guess the thing I find sad, although I certainly understand it, is how many vets who post here assume *all* protestors spat, called names, etc. That, I think, is like a protestor assuming all VVets raped someone while they were in Vietnam. Both perceptions are ridiculous, IMHO.&lt;<br><br>
&gt;Nurse Ratchet-Look up my response to you dated Feb. 8. I only can draw on my experiences when speaking on this subject. This I had done. I will re-iterate that I said a FACTION within the protest community. As far as a definition for mistreatment, again look at the Feb 8th posting. I don't know what else to do other than drawing pictures.&lt;<br><br>
Nurse Ratchet<br>
I have waited for a decent and reasonable response from you other than the constant dribble that varies not a wit from the first you ever posted.  Let me lay out exactly what my problem is with you and spell it out clear enough for a simpleton to understand.  It is very apparent that you have a very difficult time reading my posts or your ability to comprehend has been compromised by god knows what.<br><br>
Vietnam veterans were used and abused by their government. They fought in a shitty war.  Upon their homecoming, they had to deal with a ungrateful, unappreciative, and in many instances, hostile public. The worst of it, by many veterans accounts, was the apathy shown toward these veterans by the same americans which sent them off to war in the first place.  I have listed only a very few of these instances where I was personally affected.  As Vietnam Veterans, we were even shunned by vets of other wars.<br><br>
All that I have written, plus MUCH, MUCH MORE has been vastly documented from universities to the Veterans Administration.  Only those who have some kind of personal agenda or those who cannot read try dispute what I have just written.<br><br>
You want to believe that hardly any protestors blamed the returning soldiers for the &quot;sins&quot; of our country, and, thus did not vent their anger and hatred toward these same veterans.  Fine, go ahead and do that!  Since you admitted not being involved within the protest communities anyway, your word in this area has no credibility.  I have, from four individuals, just from this thread alone, who were deep within the protest community, their testimony that many protestors, DID, indeed had trouble separating the war from the warrior. That the anger and hatred for the war and system/government were vented at the most visible &quot;symbol&quot; around, the returning soldier.<br><br>
I used to believe that the worst part of the Holocaust was the millions that died in the gas chambers.  I am now revising that.  The worst part about the Holocaust is that there is those out there that want to deny that a massacre of 11 million people, let alone six million Jews, ever happened.  That the people/citizens of towns next to these camps keep on denying that they knew that these things were happening.  That the German people are still resistant to the massive proof that more than a few renagade SS soldiers took part in this slaughter.<br><br>
This, indeed is an overt attempt of taking away not just the memory of those that died in the camps, but the dignity of the dead and those that survived.  This is the ultimate RAPE of a people, to take away and deny their experiences ever existed.<br><br>
You and others are doing the same thing to the the Vietnam Veteran, albeit, on a much different level.  However, rape is rape.  You had been constantly trying to badger us into thinking that none of these things happened, that our homecoming experiences were bullshit.  Yet, the only thing you offer to substantiate your claim is that you never met any one who commited these abuses.  Tell me, how many vets do you know and have been involved in deep discussions about their homecoming?  Who would admit committing any hostilities towards veterans to you?<br><br>
Just a few years ago, during the war against Iraq, there was very vocal callings from many, many segments of the American population, that the homecoming of those veterans HAD to be different from those during the Vietnam War.  And, just about everybody went to the extra efforts to make sure that these vets were treated better upon their return.  There were even specials on TV documenting the Vietnam veteran homecoming experience in an attempt to &quot;educate&quot; why things had to be different this time around.<br><br>
Why would these things have transpired if my experiences or those of my fellow vets, never have happened?<br><br>
I have to give Dr. Spatz credit calling it on this one.  You sit in your ivory tower of academia, read a few fucken' books, and you think you have the world by the balls.  Guess what?  You don't!  You have only shown your ignorance and lack of life experiences.
